Republican Strategy to Resist Obama’s Re-Elect
Republican leaders justified their policy on the need to combat falsification in elections.
However, at the Brennan Center, the latter is considered a myth, arguing that falsifications in the United States are rarer than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 electoral falsifications in the United States in ten years.
One thing can be said with certainty: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions have partially discredited the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have enacted laws since 2009 that complicate the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon gained a new dimension after the November 2010 elections, which brought 675 new seats to the Republicans in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were passed in 2011 alone.
New electoral laws require the voter to present a photographic identity card and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish voter registration on the date of expression and remove the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to produce a photo identity card.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated legislation requiring voters to produce photographic identity cards in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Québec, American citizens do not have the same universal identity card as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11 per cent of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have an identity card with a photograph issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such a document.
However, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds $100.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25 per cent of African Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 per cent of citizens over the age of 65 and 20 per cent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo identification.
But that's not all.
Students who are considered to vote for Democrat candidates are not allowed in several states to use photo identification cards issued by their educational institution.
However, the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the licenses issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required proof of American citizenship for voting.
For the first time, such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than 10 states have enacted laws requiring voters to prove that they are US citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
Two thirds of Latin American voters are believed to vote in favour of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators initiated legislation in 2011 to abolish voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
That restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to put about 10 million citizens on the list.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 have resulted in a 17 per cent drop in the voter registration rate in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have enacted laws in five other states aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although the latter represented only 13 per cent of the total number of voters in the state.
The same was true of Latin Americans.
They represented only 11 per cent of the electorate and accounted for 24 per cent of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike white voters, who formed 76 per cent of the voters, only 46 per cent of those who voted in advance.
Of course, Democrat legislators and their supporters are actively opposed to laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws have been enacted by the Democratic Governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Prosecutor-General.
This has allowed for a partial limitation of the negative effects.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have enacted laws requiring photo identification.
Nevertheless, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly impede the exercise of the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Democratic critics condemn the biased laws that have been adopted, with a clear focus on influencing the 2012 elections in key states.
The report of the Brennan Center of 2011 shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes required by the Bench to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions have partially discredited the system of American democracy.
