This “violation” produces an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon, and therefore one of the carriers.
More stable field
The same thing happens with Higgs' boson, with the only difference that, in order for that boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be broken.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to energize it, you have to achieve very, very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond whose surface could only be shaken by a very large stone.
