To pay and sell without the help of the banks - with Bitcoin
Total contrast to the current exchange of money based on centrobanks numbered transactions between receiving parties with commission fees for processing them.
Moreover, as these technologies often occur, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, is causing financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is simultaneously a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros ...) and a protected BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows for the exchange of files between members of the same level.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a payment.
At a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, Bitcoin fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the courses are listed on Bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world's exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in the system in its October Virtual Currency Report.
He describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competing with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to ordinary currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, as “credits” used to promote in a video game that is earned in the game or that can be purchased (and sometimes exchanged).
The Facebook social network has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are both account holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network function?
Each transaction between two users actually occurs between two e-mail addresses, like e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user select another address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically using a dual-key encryption system.
