Poland and space.
Last week, at the Ministerial Meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated actively in a number of Agency projects in the following years.
But Poland began its journey to space much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were on space flights, but that was not always the case.
I recall, for example, a lecture by A. Sternfeld, who presented ideas at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933 from his pioneering work "Introduction to Space."
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, and after a few years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch Award for Induction in Space.
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books on these sciences.
Gadomsky became a famous world space propagandist, and his contribution was appreciated, including the fact that one of the craters on the back of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, Poland had built a rocket-powered rail drift.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the project.
It's not even clear whether a rocket was to be used to drive the cart or to stop it.
The only information about this is from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to think about missile arrows.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section, in cooperation with Professors Mogitski and Mégitsk.
The remaining materials show that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket, proposed by the engineer Rogozinski, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work of the author's “Air Torpedo Missile and Aeronautical Bomb” was launched.
Both projects were designed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war, the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasawy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended as a result of the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work on space has appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towerzystwo Astronomyczne).
For the first time, the issue of society is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine “Problems”, which publishes four extensive articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich offered to organize a society that would be involved in space activities.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already under way, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (SOA) has attempted to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951), and in the autumn of the PAA has become a valid member.
The following year, the first president of PAA, Kazimez Zarankevich (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in that position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful Meteorological Missile RM (Raquita Meteorologiczna), which was the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, which was able to reach a distance of 1,800 metres, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built and, in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bledovskaya Desert.
The missile was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already in a position to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have crossed 14.5 km and its mission was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The origin of the first RM-type missiles was a Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed to be two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (specified as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differ in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteorological 1A missile had a space of 0.4 litres, Meteorological 1B 0.34 litres and Meteorological 1C 0.62L.
The maximum range for all three types of flight was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed a Meteor-2 missile, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile, with a 380 kg launch weight, was able to produce a useful 10 kg load at a height of about 60 km.
The versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, under the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermashzewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
