But I ask myself, why do we have another library today?
Everyone has Internet, iPad, and e-books.
No one is willing to go to such old-fashioned libraries now, right?
The Spanishissé, a small sleeping town near Rotterdam, owns an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
In order to combat this unfortunate circumstance, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro notes, in the form of painted miniatures of iron beton.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the city's fathers realized that they had the only way to overcome the statistics: build a library here!
Vini Maas, a master of bold column charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical structures, took up the task with his usual complacency and appeared at a competition audition in 2003 with five books under the mouse and a smile on his face.
And while the jury looked around and shrugged their shoulders, the arrogant Maas folded out of his original gift a pyramid of size and completed his speech in defence of his project with the words, "Dear citizens!"
Here's my offer: "The Book Mountain" in Speichenis, so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain grew at a cost of 30 million euros.
It is part of the revitalisation project, which also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, mail and several surrounding housing and housing units for a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, "The Book Mountain" was awarded the second award of the 2012 Best Library of the Netherlands.
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch national wood competition.
Thus, the faceless suburbs, which had previously been unable to offer anything but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall whose white facades suggest a milk factory, have become richer than one modern piece of architecture.
But the most important thing is that the first public cultural building in the history of this town has appeared in Spikeniss.
A Long Way to A Book
First impression: Book Eldorado under a cheese cap.
There's only one elevator in the middle of the mountain, because true architects and readers would prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glassed on all sides - light and easily visible, burnt brick floors and elegant street lights unmistakably create a sense of public urban space.
