And once, at a single farm in Frisland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fibrous material of millimetre thickness has been used as a root pad.
It's cheap and it saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons and can then be discarded.
For the library, this painting, for the first time in these volumes, was compressed in a panel four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastic (KLP) becomes a dark, homogeneous, solid material that smells a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
They're leading 105 steps to the top.
