Sabo: "The Germans have a more important role to play."
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, the US-Europe liaison expert, Berlin, by doing so, is on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, without being overly critical of Israel.
During the rebellion in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the imposition of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made this offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, moving from the policy that the US was supposed to govern to the German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're only finding their part so far, but they're on their way to a more normal foreign policy.
Foreign policy like that of France or the UK.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a national stand independent of the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests are to a large extent different from those of other major States, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to offend the public and elite in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a totally one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculation of the Germans.
Has Germany damaged its relationship with the US by refraining from making important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the US, there is a prevailing understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
Indeed, it signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, the United States has made clear its support for the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the US and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama government, deep down, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But, of course, because of the local political situation, the Government cannot take such a position openly.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not as significant as it always seems.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all excited about Netanyahu’s politics.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the EU's most important partner on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for Germans if there were a single, uncontroversial European policy, but now it is not.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and must instead act on the basis of their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in shaping a common European position.
Clearly, this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have a more independent role to play.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take the lead?
Or is Germany still hard to lead?
Germany is not yet accustomed to this; it is still always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German sentiments manifest themselves.
The Germans are not easy to deal with.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the US.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and opinions, which is not easy.
So, the US's influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, it makes you feel uncomfortable or unloved, that's life!
Stephen Sabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and political experts from Europe and North America are jointly studying the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic ties.
"Secure of trademarks" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, Polo Ralph Laurent is also a brand.
But what is Armani Polo?
This is a fully officially registered name in China that has nothing to do with the firms from which it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names have sued.
It is also unclear whether they will be able to assert their rights.
“Foreigners are becoming increasingly difficult to defend their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer for Taylor Wessing, specializing in violations of trademark rights in the Far East.
There's a new case like this on my desk every week.
Simulators only have to add a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So Gucci is a Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way German enterprises, such as the Puma manufacturer, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with records of the Department of Trademark Registration in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name that also uses the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
The Chinese are known to be the world's champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights.
There are multi-storey stores in big cities that sell almost exclusively forgery.
However, Pattloch's cases are not the same, and on the instructions of his trustees, he opposes that Chinese enterprises formally obtain from the trademark registration office the right to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it a Ban Minpai, a passenger brand.
This word is associated with a "ban dacuan."
That's what women call hunting for rich men.
The Chinese authorities do not confess guilt
"It hurts business, it must be combated," Pattloch is convinced.
"The brand of commerce is blurred, the unique position is lost, the image suffers very much."
The financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are estimated at millions, especially in the case of expensive, copied products.
According to the CLSA Market Research Company, China is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods, with a sales volume of 15 billion euros a year.
However, it is difficult and costly to remove dubious records in the trademark registry.
The process can last up to nine years, with unclear outcomes.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed the claims, since after a long time, the name challenged became “the reality of the market”.
If the plaintiff is not lucky, he will even have to pay the plagiarism because he damaged his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also famous graphics cases.
In 2009, Daimler lost a lawsuit with the construction car manufacturer Sany, a company that had recently acquired a Putzmeister concrete-sucker company.
So the Chinese still have the right to use a logo similar to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo company Geely originally used a blue-and-white logo similar to BMW; the process was successful, and Geely had to change it.
The fashion producer Lacoste lost in China to the Hong Kong and Singapore simulators who had a famous crocodile looking the other way.
The Chinese authorities don't think they're guilty.
The CTMO Trademark Registration Authority in Beijing confirms that there were difficulties in 2010 owing to a shortage of staff and facilities.
But last year, there was a "return from emergency to normal in the working process."
For example, the number of pending objections cases decreased by 22 per cent.
Almost 57,000 such cases have been closed, an increase of 75 per cent over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81.500 claims are still awaiting processing by the agency.
Fighting it is expensive.
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This record means that China has, for the tenth consecutive time, led the list of new registrations worldwide, reports the agency.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, to a total of 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan of fees were paid.
Simplifying this means that each registration is on average worth 1280 yuan or 160 euros.
Protesting it is worth many times more, as the case of the German family enterprise Freidenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the firm has been fighting against the Chinese plagiarism.
The Germans succeeded in eliminating the illegal manufacture of counterfeit car parts.
However, the simulator reserved Chinese rights to the Freedenberg trademark.
This was a personal omission, since the names in Germany are not protected, says Hanno Ventzler, chairman of the board of Freedenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
