Bradley Manning wasn't complaining of any ill-treatment, he claims.
The prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of poor conditions of detention.
During the hearing, emphasis was placed on Manning's stay in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence demands that the case be closed on the ground that Manning's detention conditions were harsh.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had been forced to endure while in military detention.
During cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mid, Maryland, the Military Prosecutor, Major Ashden Feyn, stated that the records of the weekly visits to Manning by the prison authorities in nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defence motion to discontinue the Manning case, on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was carried out the day after Manning stated that he had intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is charged with stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the WikiLeaks web site.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Fain, along with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been completed following the visits to Manning by the Administration during his stay at Quantico prison, where he was held under strict detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he regarded the prison administration's treatment as “excellent” and the general conditions of detention as “very professionally organized”.
The reports examined do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was explicitly asked about his conditions of detention, Fein claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed verbal concern about these issues and that the Administration ' s visiting representatives had discussed these issues with him and had stated that they would deal with them but had not recorded them in writing.
"They recorded "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't raise the subject," Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained of ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission considering the suicide intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to be removed from the “injury warning” regime and eased the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that the limited regime of detention, which was lower than the suicide control regime, had been introduced to protect the prisoner and to protect the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm all right to have them cancel the injury prevention regime... so that my standard of living would improve, in my view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been arrested in Iraq and transferred to Kuwait, where he had been held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait and that he had lost consciousness once because of the heat.
He explained that it is psychologically difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is handled and what is happening in the outside world.
"My world is cramped to Camp Arifjan's base, to the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was going to die in this cage."
While in Quantico, Manning said that he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day -- alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, a blanket, slippers, some clothes and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because sleeping, or even lying down during the daytime, prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly hit by a light coming through the outside of the cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he was turning around in bed at night, he said he was woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed an official objection to the abuse of Manning in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about the statement he made during his statement on Thursday that, after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners during the morning inspection.
Manning said he couldn't cover himself with a blanket during the check.
In answer to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said that he had learned from the guard's order that he should throw a blanket to cover for himself, but he admitted that no one had direct orders to leave him.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked last night because he tried to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer he could use a pair of underpants or slaps to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, his slippers and his glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had endured during his detention and significantly reduce the sentence if Manning were found guilty by a military court, which was to begin his trial early next year.
The defence stated that it planned to invite Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, and that other charges would be challenged as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of those arrested under the strictest possible regime.
The charges brought against Manning include aiding an adversary, illegal promotion of data on the Internet, transmission of information relating to national defence and abduction of State property or documents.
If convicted under all counts of indictment, he could be sentenced to life imprisonment.
