Old Battles in the New Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and the Hamas faction can provide a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
It was a familiar, pointless debate about who had started; many buildings had been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, the majority of whom were civilians, and six Israelis had been killed; and, for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip had fallen in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the hopeless links between Israelis and Palestinians in their perpetual conflict, the Middle East has changed.
This can be seen in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have converged in a rioting storm with many established realities, and the Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that shocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons for hope of overcoming this deadly impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give rise to optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on 21 November, is being implemented, the clashes this week have only reinforced the positions of the factionists on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim to have forced Israel to retreat despite its losses.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the faction have been destroyed and 1.7 million people have been blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of the world, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements grows in the Arab world, Hamas has new powerful and rich friends.
The emerging regional leader of Turkey, who once was Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, expressed support for Hamas; her example was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas’s solemn supporters claim the establishment of an Islamist semi-month around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, which is ruled by the Hezbollah paramilitary group, to Syria, where the increasingly pro-Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad’s power, and further to Jordan, where the king’s authorities threaten Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened under President Mohammed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to Hamas support.
On the other hand, the Muslim brothers are an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more populist.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a meaningful player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the hard line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile system justified the cost of its establishment and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israelis can sleep quietly, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained steadfast; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for launching the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the Government of Binyamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that, since 2004, some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has been able to minimize the suicide problem, partly through the wall that enters the West Bank, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protects Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, in preparation for the elections scheduled for 22 January, has merged with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Liberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of condoning the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If they were to hand over all the authority in the West Bank, would they not start launching rockets from there towards Israel, as their brothers in the Gaza Strip did?
It's better to keep them out of the wall and severely suppress any attempt to lift their heads.
Proponents of the hard line may be victorious; however, their calculations may be refuted in the Arab spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and other countries, are not very fond of Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defence portion of Israel's budget is larger than all its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of war with a regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments strengthen their own economies.
Pragmatism by President Morsi of Egypt, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, to the same extent, bear in mind the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes erupted in the Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination constituted a time bomb that would explode sooner or later in the occupied territories of Israel, like the bus that had exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression already undermines the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic dimension - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloodthirsty operations carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas have to be paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse.
There remains the only solution that is unrelentingly called for by sound representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israeli concessions in exchange for security.
The hope remains, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will enable other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which is long overdue in its decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, has a more favourable position than ever before to persuade Hamas to recognize the boundaries of the Jewish State adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also work towards reconciliation between Hamas and Fatah.
That would do more for the establishment of a Palestinian State than the upcoming vote in the United Nations, which could result in recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
Upon his return to the White House, he continued to show reluctance to engage in the solution of the problem.
This is a catastrophic short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The Unified Packing for Cigarette Act has entered into force in Australia.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and the images of disease-affected body parts are contrasted in depressing green boxes that are the same for all cigarette stamps.
The first Australian law on the same package of cigarettes and tobacco products entered into force in the world, replacing logos and colouring of different stamps with an identical box of depressing olives with depressing pictures of sick body parts and images of children whose health is undermined by the smoking of their parents.
