This decision was based on research that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
“It is obvious that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging”, explains the Minister of Health, Tanya Plybersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with children's idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest share of smokers in the world, so that these changes will not have a significant impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
