The Australian Government has banned local companies and websites from posting advertising online, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
"If you're selling tobacco and you've only got this little loophole left, the idea of promoting your product on the Internet would seem very tempting to you," explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of brand reviews written on behalf of supposedly common users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he's spared his energy and time and made a video, or is it the advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco, Australia, claims that the industry is now more engaged in adapting to new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these States have filed claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that trade relations between all these countries and Australia are very small.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tani Plybersek, the Government had discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packing laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory photographs of the dangers of smoking.
This rule has now been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India are considering the possibility of tightening their laws.
A large number of smokers in Australia do not respond to innovations.
