For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulphur to the top of the volcano on steep rock trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living with sulphur in the volcano Kawah Ijen, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulphur gas rising from the depths of the earth freezes when it comes to air.
He puts large pieces of sulphur, with a total weight of 70 kg, into two bamboo baskets, he puts the baskets on his shoulders, and he carries them up on a rocky road.
Up to the top of a volcano of 2,386 meters, it takes only 250 meters, but exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb up with a turtle’s step, struggling to maintain a balance and carefully navigating the road to avoid falling or falling off a cliff.
They know that one wrong move could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen a few years ago.
Cavah Ijena miners earn 5 eurocents for each kilogram of sulphur they produce.
Upstairs, they lay the road between tourists who photograph them, as if they were circus monkeys and were tired of carrying heavy baskets, walking three kilometers to the scales that the mining company had set up a little higher, at a height of 1,850 metres.
This is the PT Candy Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, best and not least, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for each kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocents) of petrochemical production, because it is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because the norm is 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for every walk," explains Anto, who usually carries three daily shifts.
