UNASUR Summit ends without the declaration of Lima
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, which was previously declared and theoretically signed by the seven mandatory participants.
Efe repeatedly sought access to the document signed at the sixth ordinary meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the President ' s Administration indicated on the front page that it would be handed over after closure, but then confirmed that it would be published on the Peruvian Government ' s website at a certain time.
On questions about the text, they indicated that the contents had been provided by the President of Peru, Oljanta Umala, during the press briefs.
The access of journalists to information about the Summit was always limited.
In the course of the day, only a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with a message "closed meeting, no sound."
A small amount of information that was circulating among reporters was transmitted by some UNASUR government spokespersons attending the meeting, but not Peruan.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which provoked discontent among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
The Government of the President of Peru subsequently sent an e-mail to the media with the summit's “final declaration”, but this is the Umala statement, not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was also not circulated, despite press insistence.
On the official ASPA website, it is possible to verify that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities had endeavoured to ensure that broadcast systems were provided to all journalists, but had limited access to information as much as possible.
The Summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt a verdict of the Hague Court, which resolves the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Oljanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piniera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the ruling of the International Court of Justice, which began the hearing of statements by both parties on Monday in The Hague, in the context of the accusation that Lima had put forward against Santiago.
“We will abide by and implement a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently submitting to this international court”, said Umala, next to her Chilean colleague.
“Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, covenants and international tribunals”, he added, and welcomed the hand of Umala against the background of the flags of the two countries.
The reaffirmation by both Presidents of their obedience to the International Court of Justice took place immediately after Colombia protested this week against the Pact of Bogotá, according to which it recognized submission to the verdicts of that international court following the decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua, which it considered to be wrong.
The Summit was held in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rusef; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christine Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR had been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former President, Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Oljanta Umala, was responsible for opening the debate in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon in Lima time.
The Head of State read the outcome document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and action lines had been approved for 31 South American projects, with an estimated investment of $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries would take “important steps towards the purpose of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residence agreements”.
He reported that action was being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and organized transnational crime, action to increase the availability of medicines, affordable Internet access in all corners of South America and to take into account the combined and effective risks of natural disasters”.
Since Europe is in crisis, “the economic unification (Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to broaden our productive base and anticipate a better future for our cities,” Umala added.
“We have decided to grant privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve South America's connectivity, especially in the countryside and border zones... uniting our countries and creating new economic schemes,” the Peruvian President said in a read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were from Peru and were limited to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, while two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide further details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations”, from which it is now excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united and to have good relations among neighbours was another theme emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before taking part in the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court challenged by Bogotá.
"After tomorrow (saturday), perhaps meet President Daniel Ortega," said Santos.
“We will review all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua”, he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we can deal with this in the most civilized and respectful manner possible," he added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they will be present at the inauguration of the new President of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also at the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met provisionally to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Chile, Guyana, Suriname, Paraguay and Uruguay constitute UNASUR, although the latter has been suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
